The new proposals by President Uhuru Kenyatta on how to engender peace across the continent anchor hope for a better tomorrow for many communities currently under the throes of conflict.
The tendency to broker ideas on peace and security without giving due consideration to the voices of the parties to the conflict has not had positive results.
Such approaches have tended to address superficial manifestations of the conflict instead of the root causes. The United Nations Security Council must move beyond peace keeping and encourage true dialogue among the conflicting parties for sustainable and peaceful coexistence.
During its tenure at UNSC as well as Peace and Security Council of the African Union, Kenya should push for local ownership of the processes, proposals and mechanisms of resolving the long festering and emerging conflicts in Africa and beyond.
Secondly, Nairobi must join the voices calling for timely, equitable and adequate access to the Covid-19 vaccines. The pandemic has caused economic and health havoc upon the lives of many across the continent and beyond.
Erosion of productive sectors in the backdrop of the pandemic is pushing back millions through the poverty pores. Vaccines present the much awaited opportunity to reset the lost jobs and getting economies working again.



